emics, new voices and civil society actors, this book documents the changes that have occurred in people’s everyday lives as the region moves away from a violent past. Supported with a wealth of new empirical material, the book charts the impact of devolution and conflict transformation in four parts: an overview of the changes is followed by chapters that explore the areas of space, place and human relations. The third part looks at economic and social life while a concluding chapter takes a comparative approach by addressing the differences and similarities between the Northern Irish and Scottish experiences of devolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity developmentzNorthern Ireland. 0aPeace-buildingzNorthern Ireland. 0aSocial conflictzNorthern Ireland. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2018. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh  aGood Friday Agreement.  aIreland.  across-border commerce.  adevolution.  aeconomic development.  aethno-national differences.  aeveryday life.  ahealth services.  anon-statutory Shared Education Programme.  apolitical participation.  asectarianism.  asocial segregation.1 aBell, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonnelly, Caitlin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaniel, Gladys, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinds, Bronagh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJarman, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMackay, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators